dict.string: Use this section to define Wi-Fi settings
A unique identifier for the payload, dot-delimited. Usually root PayloadIdentifier+subidentifier
The type of the payload, a reverse dns string
The version of the whole configuration profile.
This value describes the issuing organization of the profile, as displayed to the user
Type of network interface on the device.
If the network should be treated as a Legacy Hotspot or Passpoint network.
Displayed name of the wireless network
Specify whether the network that the device connects to is broadcasting its identity.
Automatically join the network without notifying users.
Users won't have an opportunity to join networks that require agreements or other information prior to network access.

If true, disables MAC address randomization for that Wi-Fi network while associated with the network. This also shows a privacy warning in Settings indicating that the network has reduced privacy protections.
If 'true', enables IPv6 on this interface.
The type of proxy configuration to use for this wireless connection.
The hostname of the proxy server.
The port used to connect to the proxy server.
The user name for the manual proxy connection.
The password for the manual proxy connection.
URL used to receive proxy settings. If no URL is specified, the device uses the web proxy autodiscovery protocol (WPAD) to discover proxies
Enable to allow direct connection if PAC is unreachable
Wireless network encryption to use when connecting. The None value is available in iOS 5.0 and later and the WPA2 value is available in iOS 8.0 and later
Specifies the password for the access point.
Display name of the Passpoint service provider.
Domain name of the Passpoint service provider.
Specify whether to connect to additional Passpoint networks pre-approved by the service provider.
Connect to roaming partner Passpoint networks
Enter a series of digits corresponding to one of the service provider's Passpoint network.
Enter the known NAI realm names.
The HESSID used for Wi-Fi Hotspot 2.0 negotiation.
Select "Login Window" to authenticate the Mac to the network when the user logs in.

For EAP-TLS authentication without a network payload, install the necessary identity certificates and have your users select EAP-TLS mode in the 802.1X credentials dialog that appears when they connect to the network.
An integer representing an EAP type, inside of the Accept EAP Types array.
Username. If not provided, the user may be prompted during login.
Password. If not provided, the user may be prompted during login.
If set, the user will be prompted for a password each time they connect to the network.
Array of UUIDs corresponding to the trusted certificates for this authentication.
A UUID for a trusted certificate
Certificate Common Names expected from authentication server. The wildcard * can be used to match a range of strings.
An item in the TLS Trusted Server Names array representing a Common Name of a server certificate.
Allows a dynamic trust decision by the user.
Specifies the inner authentication used by the TTLS module.

Externally visible identification (for TTLS, PEAP, and EAP-FAST). This string is used instead of the user's identity outside the encrypted tunnel. This value can be used to mask the true identity of the person using the network.
If set, the device will use an existing PAC if it's present. Otherwise the server must present its identity using a certificate.
If set, provisions the device anonymously. Note that there are known man-in-the-middle attacks for anonymous provisioning.
The minimum number of RAND values accepted from the server. 3 is the default, and 2 is allowed, but offers less security.

Use an alternate set of credentials when in System mode (AKA not a loginwindow profile). This can be used to tell EAPOLClient to use the computer password in a bound active directory scenario for authentication.
This indicates if the connection should try to use the OpenDirectory machine credentials.
An array of trusted certificates. Each entry in the array must contain certificate data that represents an anchor certificate used for verifying the server certificate.

If 'true', allows for two-factor authentication for EAP-TTLS, PEAP, or EAP-FAST. If 'false', allows for zero-factor authentication for EAP-TLS. If you don't specify a value, the default is 'true' for EAP-TLS, and 'false' for other EAP types.
Enable any kind of QoS marking.
Enable QoS for WiFi Calling, FaceTime, SMS, etc.
Add specific apps to an allow list for QoS marking.
Add specific apps to an allow list for QoS marking.
UUID of the certificate payload containing an identity used as the client credential.
If set, force a non-default authentication method. (if YES, uses certificate from PayloadCertificateUUID).
